name: PerformanceResourceTiming
description: The PerformanceResourceTiming interface enables retrieving and analyzing detailed network timing data regarding the loading of an application's resources. An application can use the timing metrics to determine, for example, the length of time it takes to fetch a specific resource, such as an XMLHttpRequest, <SVG>, image, or script.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.initiatorType
members.description: A string representing the type of resource that initiated the performance entry, as specified in PerformanceResourceTiming.initiatorType.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.nextHopProtocol
members.description: A string representing the network protocol used to fetch the resource, as identified by the ALPN Protocol ID (RFC7301).

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.workerStart
members.description: If the current context is a worker, returns the DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately before the worker is started that fetches the resource; otherwise zero is returned.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.redirectStart
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp that represents the start time of the fetch which initiates the redirect.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.redirectEnd
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately after receiving the last byte of the response of the last redirect.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.fetchStart
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately before the browser starts to fetch the resource.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.domainLookupStart
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately before the browser starts the domain name lookup for the resource.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.domainLookupEnd
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp representing the time immediately after the browser finishes the domain name lookup for the resource.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.connectStart
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately before the browser starts to establish the connection to the server to retrieve the resource.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.connectEnd
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately after the browser finishes establishing the connection to the server to retrieve the resource.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.secureConnectionStart
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately before the browser starts the handshake process to secure the current connection.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.requestStart
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately before the browser starts requesting the resource from the server.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.responseStart
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately after the browser receives the first byte of the response from the server.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.responseEnd
members.description: A DOMHighResTimeStamp immediately after the browser receives the last byte of the resource or immediately before the transport connection is closed, whichever comes first.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.transferSize
members.description: A number representing the size (in octets) of the fetched resource. The size includes the response header fields plus the response payload body.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.encodedBodySize
members.description: A number representing the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cahce), of the payload body, before removing any applied content-codings.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.decodedBodySize
members.description: A number that is the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache) of the message body, after removing any applied content-codings.

members.name: PerformanceResourceTiming.toJSON()
members.description: Returns a DOMString that is the JSON representation of the PerformanceResourceTiming object.

parameters.name: json
parameters.description: A JSON object that is the serialization of the PerformanceResourceTiming object as a map with entries from the closest inherited interface and with entries for each of the serializable attributes.
